				},
				#parent : @6,
				#content : 'A String is an indexed collection of Characters. Class String provides the abstract super class for ByteString (that represents an array of 8-bit Characters) and WideString (that represents an array of  32-bit characters).  In the similar manner of LargeInteger and SmallInteger, those subclasses are chosen accordingly for a string; namely as long as the system can figure out so, the String is used to represent the given string.\r\rStrings support a vast array of useful methods, which can best be learned by browsing and trying out examples as you find them in the code.\r\r## Substrings and slicing\r\rA number of selectors can be used to get substrings. `String>>#lines` will return a colection containing substrings separated by `\\\\n`, `\\\\r`, or `\\\\r\\\\n`; `String>>#trim` will return a substring with whitespace removed from the beginning and end. \r\rObtaining parts of a string can also be achieved using numbered indices, also known as slicing. There are shortcut methods for some common operations that are often inherited from `SequenceableCollection` inclusing `allButFirst`, `allButLast`, `first`, or `last`.\r\r```\rs := \'abcdefg\'.\r\rs first. "$a"\rs allButFirst.  "bcdefg"\r\rs last.  "$g"\rs allButLast.  "abcdef"\r\r"pass a number argument to change the number of characters removed/kept"\r\rs first: 2.  "ab"  \rs allButFirst: 2.  "cdefg"\r\rs last: 2.  "fg"\rs allButLast: 2.  "abcde"\r```\r\rTo get the middle of a string use `SequenceableCollection>>#copyFrom:to:`\r\r```\rs := \'abcdefg\'.\rs copyFrom: 2 to: 6. "bcdef"\r```\r\rTo count back from the end of the string use the `size` selector\r```\rs := \'abcdefg\'\rs copyFrom: 2 to: s size - 1 \r```\r\r## Formatting\r\rStrings have a `String>>#format:` selector that can be used for interpolating other objects.\rThe "string template" can either have numbers between curly bracket characters (`{` and `}`)\rwhere the argument to format is a collection where values are indexed by number. Or pass in\ra `HashedCollection` where the placeholders are the keys of the collection\r```\r\'ab {1} ef {2}\' format: {\'cd\'. \'gh\'}.  "ab cd ef gh"\r\r\'ab {one} ef {two}\' format: \r    (Dictionary with: #one -> \'cd\' with: #two -> \'gh\').\r```\r\r`String>>#contractTo:` is also useful for shortening strings to a particular length by replacing \rmiddle characters.\r\r## Copying and Streaming\rAs well as the `format:` selector it is possible to build up a string using contatenation with\r`SequenceableCollection>>#,` \r\r```\ra := \'abc\'.\rb := \' easy as \'.\rc := \'123\'.\ra , b , c.  "abc easy as 123"\r```\rOr alternatively, construct a string from a stream using `SequenceableCollection class>>#streamContents:`.\r\r```\rs := String streamContents: [ :stream |\r\t  stream nextPutAll: \'abcdefg\';\r\t  space;\r\t  nextPutAll: \'123456\';\r\t  space.\r\t  \'7890\' putOn: stream. ].  "abcdefg 123456 7890"\r```\r\r## Finding/Searching\r\rSimple reqular expression type searching can be performed using `String>>#match:`, which has similar\rsymantics as "globbing" in a shell. The reciever is a template string where the `#` character matches any single character and the `*` character matches any number of characters. A `Boolean` object is returned. \r```\r\'#abb*cdch\' match: \'4abbadskfakjdfadiadfnvcdch\'  "true"\r```\r\rFor more complex matching use `String>>#matchesRegex:` which is an extension method implmented by `RxMatcher`. See the help documentation on regular expressions `HelpBrowser openOn: RegexHelp.`\r',
				#stamp : ''
			},
			#classVariables : OrderedCollection [
